<statement>
<p>A triangle has sides with lengths <m>\displaystyle{a}={7.00}</m>, <m>\displaystyle{b}={9.87}</m>, and <m>\displaystyle{c}={10.52}</m>. Calculate all of the angles of this triangle.</p>
<p>A=<fillin characters="4" /> (across from side of length <m>\displaystyle{a}={7.00}</m>)</p>
<p>
  B=<fillin characters="4" /> (across from side of length <m>\displaystyle{b}={9.87}</m>)</p>
<p>
  C=<fillin characters="4" /> (across from side of length <m>\displaystyle{c}={10.52}</m>)</p>
<p>Round to two decimal places.</p>


</statement>
<solution>
<p><ul><li>40</li><li>65</li><li>75.95</li></ul></p><p>Because we have all three sides, we can use the law of cosines for the first angle.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{7}^{{2}}={9.87}^{{2}}+{10.52}^{{2}}-{2}{\left({9.87}\right)}{\left({10.52}\right)}{\cos{{\left({A}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{49}={97.4169}+{110.6704}-{207.6648}{\cos{{\left({A}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{159.0873}=-{207.6648}{\cos{{\left({A}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{0.76607735157812}={\cos{{\left({A}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{A}={39.997066568631}={40}</m>.</p>
<p>For a second angle, we can use the shorter law of sines.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle\frac{{\sin{{\left({39.997066568631}\right)}}}}{{7.00}}=\frac{{\sin{{\left({B}\right)}}}}{{9.87}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{1.0533635800787}={\sin{{\left({B}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{B}={\arcsin{{\left({1.0533635800787}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{B}={64.995586268622}\approx{65}</m></p>
<p>The third angle we can calculate using the angle sum property.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{39.997066568631}+{64.995586268622}+{C}={180}^{\circ}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{C}={75.953389211487}\approx{75.95}</m></p>

</solution>
</myopenmath>

